00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:27,527
I know you don't like leaking,
but let us reach out to the press.

485
00:22:33,449 --> 00:22:35,033
Okay.

486
00:22:37,252 --> 00:22:39,453
Mr. Flowers,

487
00:22:39,454 --> 00:22:41,857
there's a call for you...
Bob Willumstad from A.I.G.

488
00:22:41,858 --> 00:22:44,275
He's very insistent.

489
00:22:49,197 --> 00:22:51,365
Mr. Flowers.

490
00:22:51,366 --> 00:22:53,733
My people tell me
you're the man to talk to.

491
00:22:53,734 --> 00:22:55,267
We've got a real
problem here.

492
00:22:55,268 --> 00:22:56,835
Yeah? What kind
of problem?

493
00:22:56,836 --> 00:23:00,105
It looks very much like we are
about to run out of cash.

494
00:23:00,106 --> 00:23:01,540
A.I.G.?

495
00:23:01,541 --> 00:23:03,642
We've sent over a document.
It's a spreadsheet.

496
00:23:03,643 --> 00:23:06,544
It's confidential, of course,
but it might give you some insight.

497
00:23:06,545 --> 00:23:09,214
I'm in the middle of Lehman.
I'm working with B of A.

498
00:23:09,215 --> 00:23:12,117
Is there any way
you could come over tomorrow?

499
00:23:12,118 --> 00:23:14,219
I'll take a look
at the numbers

500
00:23:14,220 --> 00:23:16,504
and we'll talk.

501
00:23:21,494 --> 00:23:23,812
Mr. Flowers.

502
00:23:27,067 --> 00:23:28,801
<i>Somebody put
the TV on.</i>

503
00:23:28,802 --> 00:23:31,387
CNBC's talking
about Lehman.

504
00:23:35,909 --> 00:23:39,213
...Person familiar
with Paulson's...

505
00:23:39,214 --> 00:23:41,382
Treasury Secretary
Hank Paulson's thinking,

506
00:23:41,383 --> 00:23:43,917
and he is saying there will
be no government money

507
00:23:43,918 --> 00:23:46,219
<i>in the resolution
of this situation.</i>

508
00:23:46,220 --> 00:23:48,889
They're saying two things
make the Lehman deal different:

509
00:23:48,890 --> 00:23:51,091
The market's been aware
and had time to prepare

510
00:23:51,092 --> 00:23:53,460
for over six months;
And the second is...

511
00:23:53,461 --> 00:23:56,029
Is that just
TV bullshit,

512
00:23:56,030 --> 00:23:59,314
or is that Paulson
sending us a message?

513
00:24:00,100 --> 00:24:01,717
Chris?

514
00:24:08,743 --> 00:24:10,627
Yeah? Sorry.

515
00:24:13,680 --> 00:24:14,998
What exactly does

516
00:24:14,999 --> 00:24:17,349
"a person familiar with
the Treasury Secretary" mean?

517
00:24:17,350 --> 00:24:19,484
That could mean
a lot of things.

518
00:24:19,485 --> 00:24:21,252
Did one of your
staffers do this?

519
00:24:21,253 --> 00:24:23,387
Please tell me someone got fired
10 minutes ago.

520
00:24:23,388 --> 00:24:25,605
The leak came from me.

521
00:24:27,358 --> 00:24:29,192
Hank, a public statement
like that

522
00:24:29,193 --> 00:24:31,194
can have a lot of
unintended consequences.

523
00:24:31,195 --> 00:24:33,162
We had to send a message
to the other banks.

524
00:24:33,163 --> 00:24:34,376
They need to step up.

525
00:24:34,377 --> 00:24:36,440
I don't have another rabbit
I can pull out of my hat.

526
00:24:37,401 --> 00:24:40,136
Rodgin Cohen
just called me.

527
00:24:40,137 --> 00:24:43,542
The B of A team is sitting there
playing brick breaker on their phones.

528
00:24:43,543 --> 00:24:45,012
They don't want this deal.

529
00:24:45,013 --> 00:24:47,516
The deal is hanging
by a thread

530
00:24:47,517 --> 00:24:49,386
because the closer
they get to Lehman

531
00:24:49,387 --> 00:24:51,689
the more it looks
like a toxic waste dump.

532
00:24:51,690 --> 00:24:55,126
Which is why at the end of the day
we may have to help them,

533
00:24:55,127 --> 00:24:58,863
which would be a lot easier
if we didn't publicly state that...

534
00:24:58,864 --> 00:25:00,965
We can't, Tim.
Legally we can't.

535
00:25:00,966 --> 00:25:03,268
Legally we haven't
figured out

536
00:25:03,269 --> 00:25:07,138
how yet.

537
00:25:07,139 --> 00:25:11,109
I am concerned

538
00:25:11,110 --> 00:25:13,777
we are limiting
our options

539
00:25:13,778 --> 00:25:17,046
at a time when we have
very few,

540
00:25:17,047 --> 00:25:19,230
if any, available.

541
00:25:21,650 --> 00:25:25,286
I want all the C.E.O.s
in a room.

542
00:25:25,287 --> 00:25:27,255
We've got the weekend.

543
00:25:27,256 --> 00:25:29,658
We lock them in a room
at the Fed

544
00:25:29,659 --> 00:25:33,363
and we don't let them out until
they have a solution on Lehman.

545
00:25:33,364 --> 00:25:35,398
Your oatmeal's
getting cold.

546
00:25:35,399 --> 00:25:38,583
They'll figure it out.
They'll all throw in some money.

547
00:25:40,102 --> 00:25:42,103
Well, Tim is
advocating strongly

548
00:25:42,104 --> 00:25:44,139
that we reconsider
some kind of Fed support.

549
00:25:44,140 --> 00:25:46,374
Tim wants us to pick up
the tab on everyone.

550
00:25:46,375 --> 00:25:48,909
I can't be
Mr. bailout.

551
00:25:48,910 --> 00:25:52,446
The Lehman hole is
twice what Bear's was.

552
00:25:52,447 --> 00:25:54,447
Investors are pulling
their accounts.

553
00:25:54,448 --> 00:25:57,016
You want to lend
into a run?

554
00:25:57,017 --> 00:25:59,251
What about Barclays?
Are they still interested?

555
00:25:59,252 --> 00:26:02,088
They can't afford the risk
any more than B of A can.

556
00:26:02,089 --> 00:26:05,626
I don't doubt your ability to talk
anybody into submission,

557
00:26:05,627 --> 00:26:07,795
but it is still
a long shot.

558
00:26:07,796 --> 00:26:11,666
And there's a very real possibility
that Lehman goes under.

559
00:26:11,667 --> 00:26:15,136
There's a deal
to be made here.

560
00:26:15,137 --> 00:26:17,938
I'm gonna make the deal.

561
00:26:17,939 --> 00:26:20,041
<i>With just a little more
than an hour</i>

562
00:26:20,042 --> 00:26:21,909
<i>left until
the market closes,</i>

563
00:26:21,910 --> 00:26:24,312
<i>shares of Lehman Brothers
have taken another tumble.</i>

564
00:26:24,313 --> 00:26:26,381
<i>The stock is now
trading at a new low...</i>

565
00:26:26,382 --> 00:26:28,318
<i>under $4 a share.</i>

566
00:26:28,319 --> 00:26:30,320
<i>And judging from
the selling,</i>

567
00:26:30,321 --> 00:26:33,239
<i>there doesn't appear to be
a bottom in sight.</i>

568
00:26:35,860 --> 00:26:37,862
So Blankfein
has a speech

569
00:26:37,863 --> 00:26:39,931
he's trying to get out of,
but the rest have confirmed.

570
00:26:39,932 --> 00:26:42,400
- Tell him it's not optional.
- Yeah.

571
00:26:42,401 --> 00:26:44,901
Good afternoon, Chairman.
Thank you so much for joining us.

572
00:26:44,902 --> 00:26:46,336
Whose plane is this?

573
00:26:46,337 --> 00:26:48,304
Uh, that's a rental.

574
00:26:48,305 --> 00:26:50,773
Hank put it
on his card.

575
00:26:50,774 --> 00:26:53,676
Sir, you know Neel and
Michele Davis, public affairs.

576
00:26:53,677 --> 00:26:54,944
Hi. Pleasure.

577
00:26:54,945 --> 00:26:56,645
This is Dan Jester...
our new numbers guy.

578
00:26:56,646 --> 00:26:57,623
Hi.

579
00:26:57,624 --> 00:26:59,149
I've talked him into
coming out of retirement.

580
00:26:59,150 --> 00:27:01,652
- Excuse me? Retirement?
- He was with us at Goldman.

581
00:27:01,653 --> 00:27:04,019
Got anybody at Treasury
who wasn't at Goldman?

582
00:27:04,020 --> 00:27:05,853
Chairman,
just to be clear,

583
00:27:05,854 --> 00:27:07,922
there's no question of
conflict of interest.

584
00:27:07,923 --> 00:27:10,557
Hank sold all of his Goldman stock
before he took office.

585
00:27:10,558 --> 00:27:12,292
I wasn't implying
anything.

586
00:27:12,293 --> 00:27:14,060
Sorry.
We're a little touchy

587
00:27:14,061 --> 00:27:16,762
about the whole
government-Sachs thing.

588
00:27:16,763 --> 00:27:18,680
Shall we?

589
00:27:21,667 --> 00:27:24,235
B of A keeps finding
more toxic assets.

590
00:27:24,236 --> 00:27:26,271
They want you
to reconsider a Jamie deal.

591
00:27:26,272 --> 00:27:28,172
They'll split the first
billion in losses,

592
00:27:28,173 --> 00:27:30,107
but they want you on the hook
for the next 40.

593
00:27:30,108 --> 00:27:32,342
You did it for Bear.

594
00:27:32,343 --> 00:27:34,643
Greg, let me
get back to you.

595
00:27:34,644 --> 00:27:37,112
What do I have to...
tattoo it on my forehead?

596
00:27:37,113 --> 00:27:38,780
We are not
bailing out Lehman.

597
00:27:38,781 --> 00:27:40,448
Wall Street has
a gambling problem.

598
00:27:40,449 --> 00:27:42,483
If government keeps
covering their losses,

599
00:27:42,484 --> 00:27:44,702
they never learn
anything.

600
00:27:45,453 --> 00:27:47,154
What?

601
00:27:47,155 --> 00:27:49,923
I didn't know if you wanted
to keep lecturing me on moral hazard

602
00:27:49,924 --> 00:27:52,658
or if I should just
call B of A back.

603
00:27:52,659 --> 00:27:54,762
We need to keep them at the table

604
00:27:54,763 --> 00:27:56,931
until they come up with
a private-sector solution.

605
00:27:56,932 --> 00:27:59,433
Tell them
to stay with us.

606
00:27:59,434 --> 00:28:01,636
<i>- Alistair, hello.
- Hello, Henry.</i>

607
00:28:01,637 --> 00:28:03,888
Hold on one second.

608
00:28:04,940 --> 00:28:06,941
Chancellor of
the Exchequer.

609
00:28:06,942 --> 00:28:10,345
<i>I understand Barclays is one of
your potential buyers for Lehman.</i>

610
00:28:10,346 --> 00:28:13,248
<i>My banks are already under
a great deal of stress.</i>

611
00:28:13,249 --> 00:28:15,550
<i>They don't want
to become overextended.</i>

612
00:28:15,551 --> 00:28:17,819
Lehman is problematic,
but there's value there.

613
00:28:17,820 --> 00:28:20,121
We will find a way
to make it attractive.

614
00:28:20,122 --> 00:28:22,323
Just stay with us.

615
00:28:22,324 --> 00:28:23,958
<i>Talk soon.</i>

616
00:28:23,959 --> 00:28:25,393
Bye.

617
00:28:25,394 --> 00:28:27,395
We'll keep Barclays
in the mix,

618
00:28:27,396 --> 00:28:30,231
but B of A is still
our best bet.

619
00:28:30,232 --> 00:28:33,668
We've got the C.E.O.s of every
major bank coming here tonight.

620
00:28:33,669 --> 00:28:37,038
We have to make it clear
that this their problem,

621
00:28:37,039 --> 00:28:40,440
that we are their advisors
and their allies,

622
00:28:40,441 --> 00:28:44,627
but we are not
their safety net.

623
00:28:45,779 --> 00:28:47,596
What should we expect
from these guys?

624
00:28:58,126 --> 00:29:00,127
<i>Jamie is smart.</i>

625
00:29:00,128 --> 00:29:02,229
<i>He doesn't have as much
cash to work with</i>

626
00:29:02,230 --> 00:29:04,931
<i>since he bought Bear.</i>

627
00:29:04,932 --> 00:29:07,733
<i>Lloyd's a superstar.</i>

628
00:29:07,734 --> 00:29:10,502
<i>Goldman's the smartest
shop on the block.</i>

629
00:29:10,503 --> 00:29:12,505
<i>And just because
I used to be his boss,</i>

630
00:29:12,506 --> 00:29:16,008
<i>it doesn't mean
he's gonna listen to me.</i>

631
00:29:16,009 --> 00:29:18,911
<i>John Mack used to run
around the floor screaming,</i>

632
00:29:18,912 --> 00:29:22,682
<i>"there's blood in the water!
Let's go kill someone!"</i>

633
00:29:22,683 --> 00:29:25,368
<i>He's a fighter.</i>

634
00:29:27,019 --> 00:29:28,886
<i>Thain was my number two
at Goldman.</i>

635
00:29:28,887 --> 00:29:30,887
<i>He's selfish.
He's a pragmatist.</i>

636
00:29:30,888 --> 00:29:34,840
<i>He knows... if Lehman goes,
Merrill's next.</i>

637
00:29:35,993 --> 00:29:39,429
<i>Vikram Pandit is the new guy
at Citigroup.</i>

638
00:29:39,430 --> 00:29:42,198
<i>No one knows
if he's running Citi</i>

639
00:29:42,199 --> 00:29:44,550
<i>or if Citi's
running him.</i>

640
00:30:07,286 --> 00:30:11,455
Thanks for coming down here
on such short notice.

641
00:30:11,456 --> 00:30:13,524
Monday morning Lehman
will no longer be able

642
00:30:13,525 --> 00:30:15,810
to honor
its obligations.

643
00:30:17,864 --> 00:30:21,133
<i>We have two potential buyers...
B of A and Barclays.</i>

644
00:30:21,134 --> 00:30:23,435
Neither will take the company
unless someone else

645
00:30:23,436 --> 00:30:25,737
finances part of the deal.

646
00:30:25,738 --> 00:30:29,357
The government is not
in a position to step in.

647
00:30:30,543 --> 00:30:33,544
I did the last one.
You're gonna do this one.

648
00:30:33,545 --> 00:30:34,945
Where is Dick Fuld?

649
00:30:34,946 --> 00:30:37,213
Dick's in no condition
to make any decisions.

650
00:30:37,214 --> 00:30:40,383
<i>We're breaking you
into three groups.</i>

651
00:30:40,384 --> 00:30:43,220
The first one
will try to value

652
00:30:43,221 --> 00:30:45,156
Lehman's toxic assets.

653
00:30:45,157 --> 00:30:47,226
<i>The second one will work
on some sort of structure</i>

654
00:30:47,227 --> 00:30:49,429
<i>for you all to invest
in Lehman.</i>

655
00:30:49,430 --> 00:30:53,134
And the third one works
on the lights-out plan.

656
00:30:53,135 --> 00:30:55,570
If Lehman files for bankruptcy,
we need to figure out

657
00:30:55,571 --> 00:30:57,872
how to contain the damage
to the rest of you.

658
00:30:57,873 --> 00:30:59,074
Christ.

659
00:30:59,075 --> 00:31:01,043
We've all seen
this coming for miles.

660
00:31:01,044 --> 00:31:04,248
I don't think the Lehman bankruptcy
takes down our firms.

661
00:31:04,249 --> 00:31:06,886
What, are we
crossing our fingers?

662
00:31:06,887 --> 00:31:09,555
You're asking us
to save a competitor.

663
00:31:09,556 --> 00:31:12,025
Let's not act like you're
doing us a favor.

664
00:31:12,026 --> 00:31:16,230
Gentlemen, gentlemen,
you are great Americans

665
00:31:16,231 --> 00:31:18,198
undertaking
a patriotic duty.

666
00:31:18,199 --> 00:31:20,966
<i>Your travail
will earn you</i>

667
00:31:20,967 --> 00:31:24,435
<i>the love and gratitude
of your country.</i>

668
00:31:24,436 --> 00:31:26,703
I think it was Thomas Paine
who said that these are...

669
00:31:26,704 --> 00:31:28,904
Lehman is a trading partner
for every bank in this room.

670
00:31:28,905 --> 00:31:31,706
<i>And their failure will be a
massive blow to all of you.</i>

671
00:31:31,707 --> 00:31:33,440
<i>This is
your problem.</i>

672
00:31:33,441 --> 00:31:35,908
We can all argue about
how we got here...

673
00:31:35,909 --> 00:31:38,243
deregulation,
derivatives,

674
00:31:38,244 --> 00:31:40,011
Dick Fuld made
bad decisions.

675
00:31:40,012 --> 00:31:43,648
<i>We're all responsible.
It's a catastrophic mess.</i>

676
00:31:43,649 --> 00:31:46,049
<i>The government's done
whatever it can do.</i>

677
00:31:46,050 --> 00:31:47,417
<i>It's on you now.</i>

678
00:31:47,418 --> 00:31:50,386
<i>You need to fix it
and you need to pay for it.</i>

679
00:31:50,387 --> 00:31:53,856
Let me be clear:

680
00:31:53,857 --> 00:31:55,858
We will remember

681
00:31:55,859 --> 00:31:58,677
anyone who's not helpful.

682
00:32:21,484 --> 00:32:23,919
<i>Do you notice a little
pattern here?</i>

683
00:32:23,920 --> 00:32:26,722
<i>We don't deal with things until there's
some kind of emergency on the table.</i>

684
00:32:26,723 --> 00:32:29,024
<i>Yeah, we don't deal
with things until Friday...</i>

685
00:32:29,025 --> 00:32:31,393
<i>Some kind of a weekend thing.
When are we gonna figure out</i>

686
00:32:31,394 --> 00:32:33,596
<i>exactly how to handle the failure
of an investment bank?</i>

687
00:32:33,597 --> 00:32:35,164
<i>Well, let's do it
over a weekend.</i>

688
00:32:35,165 --> 00:32:37,199
Just I talked to a person
who is monitoring

689
00:32:37,200 --> 00:32:39,536
The situation out there,
and the person said

690
00:32:39,537 --> 00:32:42,873
they all want the same deal
Jamie Dimon got,

691
00:32:42,874 --> 00:32:44,908
and they're not
going to get it.

692
00:32:44,909 --> 00:32:47,344
Just a heads up...
Chris Flowers is in the lobby.

693
00:32:47,345 --> 00:32:50,397
He's consulting
for B of A on Lehman.

694
00:32:52,116 --> 00:32:54,951
Hank pushed Flowers
out of Goldman.

695
00:32:54,952 --> 00:32:56,720
Yesterday we thought
Lehman was holding

696
00:32:56,721 --> 00:32:58,655
$30 billion in crap.
Today it's $70...

697
00:32:58,656 --> 00:33:02,156
$70 billion in assets that
we're valuing with a dartboard.

698
00:33:02,157 --> 00:33:03,525
No, we're gonna
work this out.

699
00:33:03,526 --> 00:33:05,827
Unless you step in,
we're ending this.

700
00:33:05,828 --> 00:33:07,261
Don't forget
about Dick.

701
00:33:07,262 --> 00:33:09,063
Yeah, Dick Fuld
keeps calling,

702
00:33:09,064 --> 00:33:10,981
hammering us
to raise the price.

703
00:33:12,601 --> 00:33:14,751
Excuse me.

704
00:33:19,107 --> 00:33:22,008
$70 fucking billion

705
00:33:22,009 --> 00:33:25,678
and no collateral?

706
00:33:25,679 --> 00:33:28,247
<i>If Lehman Brothers fails
this weekend,</i>

707
00:33:28,248 --> 00:33:30,549
there's little doubt
amongst the people I speak to

708
00:33:30,550 --> 00:33:32,650
that Merrill Lynch
will be next.

709
00:33:32,651 --> 00:33:34,987
Confidence is a very
fragile thing.

710
00:33:34,988 --> 00:33:38,692
And in our financial markets
it is eroding very quickly.

711
00:33:38,693 --> 00:33:40,926
Lehman's not gonna
make it.

712
00:33:40,927 --> 00:33:43,928
We're next.
We need to do something right now.

713
00:33:43,929 --> 00:33:46,197
B of A's the only one
out there.

714
00:33:46,198 --> 00:33:48,633
I can put in a call.
It screws Lehman, but...

715
00:33:48,634 --> 00:33:51,535
Lehman screwed themselves.
Paulson has drawn a line in the sand.

716
00:33:51,536 --> 00:33:53,470
Lehman is dead.

717
00:33:53,471 --> 00:33:55,855
Make the call.

718
00:33:58,541 --> 00:34:01,745
We'd like you guys
to look at taking a stake in Merrill,

719
00:34:01,746 --> 00:34:04,781
something in
the neighborhood of 10%.

720
00:34:04,782 --> 00:34:08,218
Well, I don't know
if I can generate any interest in 10%,

721
00:34:08,219 --> 00:34:11,321
but if the whole
company's in play,

722
00:34:11,322 --> 00:34:14,590
I bet that's something
