1691
01:24:16,818 --> 01:24:19,553
<i>The banks need
money now.</i>

1692
01:24:19,554 --> 01:24:23,090
If cash injections are the most
efficient way to stabilize them,

1693
01:24:23,091 --> 01:24:26,259
then we can't back off

1694
01:24:26,260 --> 01:24:28,261
because we're uncomfortable
being the men

1695
01:24:28,262 --> 01:24:30,597
who nationalized
a few American banks.

1696
01:24:30,598 --> 01:24:32,266
It's faster,
that's for sure.

1697
01:24:32,267 --> 01:24:34,368
It will push us back
off the precipice, yes,

1698
01:24:34,369 --> 01:24:37,972
unfreeze the system.

1699
01:24:37,973 --> 01:24:40,741
We give them some money

1700
01:24:40,742 --> 01:24:44,194
and they lend it out.

1701
01:24:47,916 --> 01:24:49,416
The motion is adopted.

1702
01:24:49,417 --> 01:24:51,785
After rejecting the Bush
Administration's T.A.R.P. Plan

1703
01:24:51,786 --> 01:24:54,422
only four days ago,
the House passed it today.

1704
01:24:54,423 --> 01:24:56,283
The big question now...

1705
01:24:56,284 --> 01:24:58,126
whether investors will take
comfort in the news.

1706
01:24:58,127 --> 01:25:00,128
<i>Current indicators show
the stock market</i>

1707
01:25:00,129 --> 01:25:03,315
<i>is continuing
its freefall.</i>

1708
01:25:21,519 --> 01:25:22,885
<i>Hello.</i>

1709
01:25:22,886 --> 01:25:25,221
Warren, it's Hank.

1710
01:25:25,222 --> 01:25:28,324
I... I... I'm sorry.
It's late.

1711
01:25:28,325 --> 01:25:30,661
Am I waking you?

1712
01:25:30,662 --> 01:25:33,130
<i>No, not at all.</i>

1713
01:25:33,131 --> 01:25:35,299
Can I pick your brain
for a minute?

1714
01:25:35,300 --> 01:25:38,101
<i>Sure.
What's the problem?</i>

1715
01:25:38,102 --> 01:25:41,272
How do you get
a healthy bank...

1716
01:25:41,773 --> 01:25:44,791
to accept
a capital injection?

1717
01:26:38,665 --> 01:26:41,167
I had to drag my ass
all the way here from California.

1718
01:26:41,168 --> 01:26:43,102
They wouldn't even
tell my why.

1719
01:26:43,103 --> 01:26:45,004
Nobody knows
what this is about?

1720
01:26:45,005 --> 01:26:47,256
Nope.

1721
01:26:52,279 --> 01:26:53,980
Talk to Jamie?

1722
01:26:53,981 --> 01:26:56,250
Yep. He'll be fine.

1723
01:26:56,251 --> 01:26:58,119
Did you tell him
what was coming?

1724
01:26:58,120 --> 01:27:00,255
Uh, did I tell him we're about
to make him swallow

1725
01:27:00,256 --> 01:27:03,625
a capital injection
he doesn't need? No.

1726
01:27:03,626 --> 01:27:06,328
I... I told him
we need his help

1727
01:27:06,329 --> 01:27:09,916
and I asked him very politely
not to fuck with us today.

1728
01:27:11,135 --> 01:27:12,619
He got it.

1729
01:27:13,771 --> 01:27:15,989
She's here.

1730
01:27:20,813 --> 01:27:22,814
Gentlemen.

1731
01:27:22,815 --> 01:27:24,584
We think this is
gonna work?

1732
01:27:24,585 --> 01:27:27,103
Oh yeah.
They're gonna love it.

1733
01:27:49,079 --> 01:27:51,047
We are of the view

1734
01:27:51,048 --> 01:27:53,050
that the United States
needs

1735
01:27:53,051 --> 01:27:55,752
to take strong,
decisive action

1736
01:27:55,753 --> 01:27:58,921
to arrest the stress

1737
01:27:58,922 --> 01:28:02,457
in our financial system.

1738
01:28:02,458 --> 01:28:05,526
Through our new
T.A.R.P. Authority,

1739
01:28:05,527 --> 01:28:08,495
Treasury will purchase

1740
01:28:08,496 --> 01:28:10,764
preferred stock

1741
01:28:10,765 --> 01:28:13,849
in each of the banks
represented in this room.

1742
01:28:16,035 --> 01:28:18,503
<i>That stock will yield 5%
the first five years,</i>

1743
01:28:18,504 --> 01:28:21,472
<i>9% after that.</i>

1744
01:28:21,473 --> 01:28:24,174
We give you money;
You lend it out.

1745
01:28:24,175 --> 01:28:27,610
It will unfreeze credit,
stabilize the banks,

1746
01:28:27,611 --> 01:28:29,512
restore confidence.

1747
01:28:29,513 --> 01:28:31,613
<i>Everyone will be
better off</i>

1748
01:28:31,614 --> 01:28:33,648
with more capital
in the system.

1749
01:28:33,649 --> 01:28:35,716
And that is why

1750
01:28:35,717 --> 01:28:39,586
all nine of you

1751
01:28:39,587 --> 01:28:42,605
will participate
in the program.

1752
01:28:45,926 --> 01:28:47,727
Some of us don't need
any capital.

1753
01:28:47,728 --> 01:28:50,231
You all need capital.

1754
01:28:50,232 --> 01:28:52,800
You have no idea what the
market's gonna look like in a year.

1755
01:28:52,801 --> 01:28:54,902
Neither do you.

1756
01:28:54,903 --> 01:28:56,903
I'm not one of you
New York guys

1757
01:28:56,904 --> 01:28:58,872
with your
fancy products.

1758
01:28:58,873 --> 01:29:01,775
Well, why am I in this room
talking about bailing you out?

1759
01:29:01,776 --> 01:29:05,378
The stronger banks will serve
as cover for the weaker banks.

1760
01:29:05,379 --> 01:29:08,014
If just some of you take it,
the money is a signal

1761
01:29:08,015 --> 01:29:11,117
that a bank is too weak to survive.
The market will devour it.

1762
01:29:11,118 --> 01:29:13,853
How much are we
talking about?

1763
01:29:13,854 --> 01:29:16,940
$125 billion.

1764
01:29:18,927 --> 01:29:20,928
<i>Bank of America...
$15 billion.</i>

1765
01:29:20,929 --> 01:29:23,264
<i>Bank of New York Mellon...
$3 billion.</i>

1766
01:29:23,265 --> 01:29:26,800
<i>Citigroup...
$25 billion.</i>

1767
01:29:26,801 --> 01:29:30,137
<i>Goldman Sachs...
$10 billion.</i>

1768
01:29:30,138 --> 01:29:33,474
<i>J.P. Morgan...
$25 billion.</i>

1769
01:29:33,475 --> 01:29:35,743
<i>Merrill Lynch...
$10 billion.</i>

1770
01:29:35,744 --> 01:29:38,278
<i>Morgan Stanley...
$10 billion.</i>

1771
01:29:38,279 --> 01:29:41,448
<i>State Street...
$2 billion.</i>

1772
01:29:41,449 --> 01:29:43,934
<i>Wells Fargo...
$25 billion.</i>

1773
01:29:49,658 --> 01:29:53,327
What happened
to buying toxic assets?

1774
01:29:53,328 --> 01:29:54,929
Wasn't that the idea?

1775
01:29:54,930 --> 01:29:56,464
<i>It's too slow.</i>

1776
01:29:56,465 --> 01:29:58,566
You'll be dead
before we sort it out.

1777
01:29:58,567 --> 01:30:02,002
So we're just handing
the reins over to you?

1778
01:30:02,003 --> 01:30:03,670
The deal's actually
pretty good.

1779
01:30:03,671 --> 01:30:06,340
You turn your nose up at this now,
and we have to rescue you later...

1780
01:30:06,341 --> 01:30:08,141
the terms won't be
nearly as attractive.

1781
01:30:08,142 --> 01:30:10,811
It's cheap capital.
It's not the worst idea in the world.

1782
01:30:10,812 --> 01:30:12,779
Well, it is for those of us
who already have capital.

1783
01:30:12,780 --> 01:30:14,916
We will be nonvoting
shareholders.

1784
01:30:14,917 --> 01:30:17,568
This will be
a temporary measure.

1785
01:30:19,855 --> 01:30:22,022
What if we decline
to be involved?

1786
01:30:22,023 --> 01:30:25,593
The Chairman of the FDIC
is sitting right there.

1787
01:30:25,594 --> 01:30:27,294
<i>Tomorrow you'll
find out</i>

1788
01:30:27,295 --> 01:30:29,697
<i>that you're not as well-capitalized
as you think you are.</i>

1789
01:30:29,698 --> 01:30:31,699
What kind of protections
can you offer on changes

1790
01:30:31,700 --> 01:30:33,333
for compensation policy?

1791
01:30:33,334 --> 01:30:36,203
I mean, if the government
is going to become a part-owner,

1792
01:30:36,204 --> 01:30:38,205
does that mean
that the government

1793
01:30:38,206 --> 01:30:40,774
is going to dictate
compensation?

1794
01:30:40,775 --> 01:30:43,011
Are you asking me about your
bonus right now, John?

1795
01:30:43,012 --> 01:30:45,380
I'm running
a company.

1796
01:30:45,381 --> 01:30:47,382
If the Fed tells me
I can't offer

1797
01:30:47,383 --> 01:30:49,684
competitive pay
for talent,

1798
01:30:49,685 --> 01:30:52,887
you're gonna launch the biggest brain
drain this country's ever seen.

1799
01:30:52,888 --> 01:30:54,755
Is that the way you want
to run the banks?

1800
01:30:54,756 --> 01:30:56,790
Until the money is repaid
to the Treasury,

1801
01:30:56,791 --> 01:31:00,259
there will be some limitations on tax
deductions and golden parachutes.

1802
01:31:00,260 --> 01:31:02,327
- Well, there you go.
- I don't really understand

1803
01:31:02,328 --> 01:31:04,962
why there needs to be
so much tension about this.

1804
01:31:04,963 --> 01:31:06,931
The country is facing

1805
01:31:06,932 --> 01:31:09,466
the worst economy
since the Great Depression.

1806
01:31:09,467 --> 01:31:11,969
If the financial system
collapses,

1807
01:31:11,970 --> 01:31:15,022
it will take
every one of you down.

1808
01:31:23,079 --> 01:31:25,430
Give me the papers.

1809
01:31:32,653 --> 01:31:34,320
- You can't just sign it.
- Oh no?

1810
01:31:34,321 --> 01:31:37,989
- Not without your board.
- My board's on 24-hour notice.

1811
01:31:37,990 --> 01:31:40,259
I think they'll
go along with it.

1812
01:31:40,260 --> 01:31:45,012
And if they don't,
they'll fire me.

1813
01:31:50,304 --> 01:31:53,222
Anyone else?

1814
01:31:58,147 --> 01:32:00,565
Are they gonna do it?

1815
01:32:01,684 --> 01:32:03,352
They're calling
their boards.

1816
01:32:03,353 --> 01:32:05,855
- That's a good sign.
- If they do go along with this,

1817
01:32:05,856 --> 01:32:08,558
we should announce
something alongside the injections...

1818
01:32:08,559 --> 01:32:11,629
maybe a program
to buy up mortgages.

1819
01:32:11,630 --> 01:32:13,365
I'm not rushing out
some half-assed plan

1820
01:32:13,366 --> 01:32:15,167
just to make it look like
we're doing something.

1821
01:32:15,168 --> 01:32:17,604
Maybe we just beef up
the restrictions

1822
01:32:17,605 --> 01:32:20,374
on how they
spend the money...

1823
01:32:20,375 --> 01:32:22,210
something to take
the stink off.

1824
01:32:22,211 --> 01:32:25,030
Put more restrictions on it...
they won't take it.

1825
01:32:29,486 --> 01:32:31,972
One thing too many
for today.

1826
01:32:33,993 --> 01:32:35,961
They almost bring down

1827
01:32:35,962 --> 01:32:37,797
the U.S. economy
as we know it,

1828
01:32:37,798 --> 01:32:40,299
but we can't put restrictions
on how they spend

1829
01:32:40,300 --> 01:32:43,536
the $125 billion
we're giving them,

1830
01:32:43,537 --> 01:32:47,890
because they might not
take it.

1831
01:33:19,273 --> 01:33:21,540
What's this?

1832
01:33:21,541 --> 01:33:25,377
That is, um...

1833
01:33:25,378 --> 01:33:27,913
A poison dart frog.

1834
01:33:27,914 --> 01:33:31,400
Wendy took it
in Guyana.

1835
01:33:43,664 --> 01:33:46,416
Is this yours?

1836
01:33:51,005 --> 01:33:53,489
Al Capone's.

1837
01:33:55,442 --> 01:33:56,976
Eight out of the nine
are in.

1838
01:33:56,977 --> 01:33:59,012
B of A is still waiting
on its board, but...

1839
01:33:59,013 --> 01:34:01,548
it's gonna go through.

1840
01:34:01,549 --> 01:34:04,184
<i>I'll call the Speaker's
office.</i>

1841
01:34:04,185 --> 01:34:07,221
And we're gonna get you
on the phone with the President.

1842
01:34:07,222 --> 01:34:10,174
<i>Okay.</i>

1843
01:34:12,961 --> 01:34:15,796
Dow is up 900 points

1844
01:34:15,797 --> 01:34:18,315
just because
we were meeting.

1845
01:34:20,468 --> 01:34:24,505
<i>Well, that's good.</i>

1846
01:34:24,506 --> 01:34:27,074
That's good.

1847
01:34:27,075 --> 01:34:29,809
It was the right thing.

1848
01:34:29,810 --> 01:34:32,747
<i>Absolutely.</i>

1849
01:34:32,748 --> 01:34:34,716
I was prepared
for more blowback.

1850
01:34:34,717 --> 01:34:37,819
They didn't have
a choice.

1851
01:34:37,820 --> 01:34:40,338
They knew that.

1852
01:34:41,657 --> 01:34:46,428
Well, I certainly hope
that they...

1853
01:34:46,429 --> 01:34:47,846
What?

1854
01:34:49,565 --> 01:34:53,802
I hope they use the money
the way we're asking them to.

1855
01:34:53,803 --> 01:34:58,890
They will... lend it out,
won't they?

1856
01:34:59,976 --> 01:35:02,828
Of course they will.

1857
01:35:14,457 --> 01:35:16,208
Of course they will.

